ayStation re-releases came along, the following was true:<br>
<br>
Japan: Final Fantasy 1, 2 and 3 were released for the NES.<br>
Final Fantasy 4, 5 and 6 were released for the SNES.<br>
Final Fantasy 7 onwards have been released for the PS.<br>
<br>
America: Final Fantasy 1 was basically the first of the NES games.  The other two NES FF games were not released in America.<br>
&quot;Final Fantasy 2&quot; in America was actually the same game as the original &quot;Final Fantasy 4&quot; in Japan. (SNES)<br>
&quot;Final Fantasy 3&quot; in America was actually the same game as the original &quot;Final Fantasy 6&quot; in Japan. (SNES)<br>
Note that &quot;Final Fantasy 5&quot; was never released outside Japan on the SNES, nor was it translated into English.  You can get a patch for it to translate the text if you use emulators, though.<br>
<br>
UK: We have never had any official Final Fantasy releases on the SNES.  Basically, we missed out BIG TIME.<br>
<br>
Can you see where the confusion lies?  It was decided that America would get some, but not all, of the Final Fantasy games.  So the renumbering occurred.  Most gamers (i.e. those who did not investigate the import market) were none the wiser.  Until FF7 came out on the PS, and confused everyone.<br>
<br>
I would not have posted this if I didn't know what I was talking about, and I'd appreciate a little more respect if you intend to stay here, thank you.<br>
<br>
